RIP Tony Todd, love of my life (in film). These movies are so silly. After the first one, which was pretty good, all the deaths in these movies are caused purely by easily avoidable human negligence. In the most Road Runner/Wiley Coyote/Acme kind of way. Lol.

Yup, the movie is repetitive (of course, it scared the heck out of me back in the days). But still, we gotta give the devil his due:
1. It has a unique concept: no killer, no ghost, no monster. Just Death, or should I say, a malevolent unseen force known as Death.
2. To be quite frank, this franchise doesn't even need a storyline, or the connection between the installments, at all (luckily, it does). Because this concept can be reused over and over again, as long as the kills are creative (you still have a point, though. Most of the kills are cause by negligence and stupidity). Despite the cliché, they still get me hooked: I'm curious to find out who will go next, and most importantly, HOW.

Anyway, let's wait and see what this one has in store.

I’ve been looking forward to this for the past 14 years. 

First became obsessed with these at a morbidly young age (thank Happy Tree Friends), mostly my fascination with seeing death and destruction in film. Part four is probably my favorite of the bunch for its spectacle (i.e. the race car track and mall premonitions), but I also enjoy parts two and three — I have a soft spot for all the other films but it’s my preference. I remember just before part five was released, I saw a fan-made trailer for it — which predated the film by two years and accurately predicted the bridge collapse sequence! Only in this case did the fan editor combine snippets from earlier horror films to construct a rough trailer (i.e. The Mothman Prophecies, The Omen remake, The Eye and Premonition) – which look so much better than today's typical digital film processing. As I get older, I can see why I prefer the vintage Y2K-era of films to newer ones.

I hope they make more of these and come up with even crazier ideas — maybe a ship disaster, a concert venue / football stadium, ski resort, zoo, aquarium or building collapse? (Well, if you factor in this being about first responders, I’ll await to see whatever premonitions they can come up with to put a bang on the screen.) A wise decision to release this theatrically. Maybe they’ll screen the other five movies in a marathon viewing — 4DX per se? I’ll go see them in a heartbeat.

To Todd, the one and only Bludworth.

(Extreme 🤓 Warning)

Final Destination 2 established the rule that if new life is brought into the list, then it stops death's plans for that list. This grandma supposedly didn't just have a child, but a whole FAMILY descendant from her. And yet they're saying that death just...waited 20 years before getting bored and trying to kill them? Who knows how many people from the sky tower were still alive when the grandma had her first child, let alone if any were alive at all. Also, if death really was coming for her, how did she survive for so long? Clear, the longest surviving person on death's list to ultimately bite the bullet lasted only a few years I think. And that was in pure isolation in a padded room. A rule established in the SECOND movie should not have been forgotten this easily. I would've expected the life-stealing rule in the 5th movie or the self-skipping rule in the 4th to be forgotten instead. The filmmakers better have a damn good reason to apply a random exception to this. And also, cheap "remember Terry's death?" kill.

TL;DR: this movie's script violates the second movie's rule of death.

Some say this movie is unrealistic and forced. It would be better if it were purely imaginative, as horror should be, with the presence of other entities, especially since this film also gives the main character psychic abilities, rather than forcing it like this.

But they forget that in real life, unwanted things often happen simply due to carelessness, lack of awareness, recklessness, and negligence, leading to negative consequences, whether it's an accident or something else entirely.

And it leaves a mark on the audience's mind, making them paranoid and unconsciously more cautious about everything after watching.

That is what psychological horror is supposed to be.

And that's the core

If the latest theory—which I firmly believe to be true—that the five main characters in the Final Destination franchise are the cursed descendants of the people Grandma saved from the collapsing tower is accurate, it should rank among the best writing retcons I have ever seen and make perfect sense. But when you take a moment to reflect and realize one thing, it's completely crazy: if you are cursed by Death in your family tree and you have a premonition of an accident or disaster but save one, two, or more people from it, you have technically "infected" the person you saved to be cursed as well. To put it another way, the "Death curse" is a supernatural virus that, although it is intended to occur when a person dies in a particular accident, does not because of the individual's premonition; or, in other words, the premonition is a proper antibody. To make matters worse, there is a good chance that someone who has been saved by someone with the "Death curse" may spread it to their friends, family, and other acquaintances too.
Holy cow, dude. This is the type of mind-blowing writing Hollywood needs nowadays.

The British Medical Journal (BMJ): Cheng Peiming Detained Multiple Times for Practicing Falun Gong
BMJ reported on August 12, 2024 that a man spoke at an event in Washington, D.C., about how he was detained, tortured, and forced to undergo surgery in China.

The report reads, “Cheng Pei Ming, described as the ‘first known survivor’ of China’s forced organ harvesting campaign against prisoners, said that he was detained several times between 1999 and 2004 for being a practitioner of Falun Gong.

“After being sentenced to eight years in prison in 2002, Cheng said that he was tortured, and in 2004 forcibly taken to a hospital and pressured to sign consent forms for an operation after swallowing sharp objects. Despite refusing to sign, Cheng said that he was held down by guards and injected with anesthetics.”

The US PubMed also posted the URL link of the article titled “‘Tortured, drugged, and assaulted’: Chinese survivor of forced organ harvesting speaks out.”

The Irish Sun: Pure Evil
The Irish Sun carried a report on August 9, 2024 titled “PURE EVIL I had my organs harvested by China’s ‘Gestapo’ who carved up my lung & liver, says first known survivor of sick torture.”

“Cheng Pei Ming says he endured years of prison torture for practising the Falun Gong religion against the will of the Chinese Communist Party.”

The report continued, “In 2002, Cheng was imprisoned for eight years after advocating for an end to the persecution of Falun Gong by the government.

“He said one day he was taken to a hospital against his will.”

He added, “They tried to force me to sign consent forms for an operation.

“When I refused, six guards grabbed me and held me down and I was injected with something.

“The next thing I remember is being in a hospital bed with tubes in my nose and I was going in and out of consciousness.

“There was a tube with bloody liquid coming from under the bandaging that was on my side.”

The report referred to Professor Wendy Rogers, chair of International Coalition to End Transplant Abuse in China, who said, “I do not know why the Chinese doctors removed parts of Mr. Cheng’s liver and lungs, but I do know that he did not have a disease or illness requiring this surgery.

“The portion of liver removed is consistent with securing liver tissue suitable for transplantation into a child, but I have no means of knowing if this was the purpose.

“What I do know is that Mr. Cheng was surgically assaulted as part of a wider pattern of persecution, incarceration and torture, and that these events happened to him because he is a practitioner of Falun Gong.”

Man, to see Tony Todd so frail is not easy. I lived in LA for 6 months in the late 90s and saw him at a party once. Dude was so physically imposing that it was scary, but i heard him chatting with someone and even with that voice of his, he was kind and respectful. I remember first seeing him in the remake of Night of the Living Dead, and will always remember him mowing down zombies one after another. The Crow, Star Trek Next Gen and DS9, The Rock, and of course the Candyman movies. But my favorite performance of his was in The Man From Earth, a movie about an immortal man who reveals himself to the friends he made over the last 20 years on the night he is going to move on to his next life. Tony Todd is great - the whole cast is, actually, and it is a fantastic script. And his voice work is stellar, of course.

You are missed, big man. RIP.

Unfortunately, I have to deal with “Final Destination” feelings everyday. I survived a plane crash at Richmond International Airport in Richmond, VA on April 11, 2011 due to catastrophic left engine failure of my aircraft immediately after takeoff. I suffered 65% burns, 68 total surgeries (so far), 2 amputated fingers on my right hand, a completely rebuilt nose, and hundreds upon hundreds of hours of physical, occupational, and psychological therapy. There are risks to everything we do in life, and some things are simply out of our control. I suffer with PTSD and am often hyper aware, knowing something is going to happen but not the what, when, or where. It’s a terrible feeling that never subsides and is a true nightmare to experience. I truly mean this when I say live each day to the fullest, tell your loved ones how much you love them, and be grateful for everything you have. I received a 2nd chance at life, and I’m thankful for that every single day.
Bless you ❤

I mean, it’s scary if this is saying Death is legitimately influencing their actions of the people to act and behave like they do, but they way he slams the beer bottle thinking it’s safe is just an individual choice. I personally would think I’ll put it further away from the edge, or somewhere less precarious. It must be because they don’t have the benefit of watching these movies, but my god who leaves a sharpened rake under a trampoline? Who doesn’t notice a giant package car? That one annoyed me. It’s not final destination, it’s Darwin at work if you stand in the street. Say what you will about cars being a plague? But I learned very very early the world we live in means cars drive on the street and they can kill you. I learned slightly later just how mindless people who “drive” these things actually are. I think a final Final Destination movie that connects everything would be a perfect way to conclude the series. The franchise has always had a loose connection through William Bludworth and Death’s rules, but an installment that fully ties together every disaster, survivor, and event would make it feel like one big, horrifying puzzle finally being solved.

Here’s what I’d love to see:

-A reveal that the 1960s tower fire survivors were the ancestors of the previous films' survivors, making all the disasters part of one long, generational curse.

-William Bludworth’s true role finally explained—is he just an observer, or does he know a way to break Death’s cycle? Maybe he was connected to Esther and the original survivors.

-A final group of survivors from past movies coming together, realizing they were never just random victims—they were all part of a bigger, predestined event leading to one ultimate confrontation with Death.

-A shocking, mind-blowing ending—either they finally find a way to break Death’s cycle, or there’s a dark twist that shows it was all inevitable from the start.

If Bloodlines is setting this up, it could be the franchise’s way of leading into a huge, epic conclusion. I really hope the filmmakers take the opportunity to give fans something more than just another standalone entry. A true final chapter that brings everything full circle would be legendary.

“Final Destination 6,” officially titled “Final Destination: Bloodlines,” is the upcoming sixth installment in the “Final Destination” franchise. The film is described as a “reboot” due to its fresh take on the series, but it is not a traditional reboot that disregards previous films. Instead, it is considered a “requel,” blending elements of both a sequel and a reboot. This approach allows the movie to introduce new characters and storylines while maintaining continuity with the existing franchise.

So when they say "Witness the birth of death" does this mean that this is the very first Final Destination before the previous 5?

Yes and no. Technically when we see the younger version of Grandma, she might be the first one to receive premonitions. But in the trailer, we see one of her books which has drawings to previous Final Destination films, meaning this is definitely the first and last in the chronology.

@leandrotupas242 yes, this is technically how everything started in the franchise. Everything apparently started with the grandmother when she was young and from there it just trickled down through the generations of the family.

​@@CHRONICLEKAI when we see the book with references to the previous films, that is because when she initially had her premonition she also apparently saw the other family members premonitions as well.

The flashback scenes to the restaurant disaster are supposed to be the first time Death's designs were thwarted.

Chronologically, it looks like the events are going to ordered like:

1960s flashbacks > 5 > 1 > 2 > 3 > 4 > Modern time events ("Bloodlines")
​@@victoracosta4796 exactly, which is how the grandmother knows and has a book that references the previous films.
